narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned a lot about AB calculus, there was a lot of focus on basics at the beginning of the course, specifically limits and learning theorems. There was less attention at the end of the course on the broader topics, however thats to be expected now that they had built the foundation and the basic principles.
Developed the ability to think critically and apply.
This course provided the basic understanding of Single Variable Calculus, as well as the essential critical thinking skills needed to work through problems given.
I learned the basics of calculus.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I think the course could be improved through more attention on the back half of the material. I think the combination of ximeras and learning the material in class helped a lot.
I found the teachers to be knowledgable but poor in teaching methods.
I did not like how one instructor had more control of the test and could tell his/her students what to study for on the exam.
Strengths in this course could be found in the Peer Tutors and the Professors themselves, who were dedicated in attempting to teach students the provided content.

Teaching in class is not reflective of the expectations on tests. I felt that sections taught by the course head were better prepared for assessments than classes taught by graduate students. The p-sets are extra work for little gain in actual preparation because the types of questions are different.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes I would. I thought it was a straightforward course with good teaching. Some of the topics are difficult but theyre not horrible to understand if you put in the effort. The teachers are good and the classes are small to help students do their best.
I would recommend this course due to its ability to effectively challenge the mind as well as bring a strong base for the introduction of Calculus.
